{"schema_version": 2, "ts": "2026-05-11T00:00:00Z", "event": "clarify_critic", "feature": "reframe-discovery-to-principal-architect-posture", "parent_epic_loaded": false, "findings": [{"text": "The assessment rates intent clarity HIGH on the basis that the ticket explicitly states the goal but the load-bearing terms 'principal-architect posture' and 'architectural distillation' are never defined in the ticket — definition is delegated to discovery_source which the assessment never inspected.", "origin": "primary"}, {"text": "The assessment rates intent clarity HIGH while the ticket documents a recent direction reversal (DR-1 → DR-G → DR-1) with 9 DR-G carryovers folded in; the current scope is a hybrid composite that may not cohere with DR-1's core claim.", "origin": "primary"}, {"text": "The assessment rates scope boundedness HIGH but several touch points are unbounded ('rewrite §2', '§4 augment with branches') and added surfaces (architecture section, scope-envelope, three event types, uniform body template) are described by name only with no size or acceptance shape — asymmetric precision vs the removed-surface line ranges.", "origin": "primary"}, {"text": "The assessment rates scope HIGH despite three Spec-phase MUST deliverables, including a new bin/cortex-check-prescriptive-prose executable with dual-source mirroring obligations — the complexity rating omits the new bin/ executable from its enumeration.", "origin": "primary"}, {"text": "The assessment rates requirements alignment HIGH citing the no-MUST-without-evidence deferral, but the ticket itself uses MUST language ('Spec-phase MUST deliverables', 'The spec phase MUST re-walk...') without the evidence-artifact link CLAUDE.md requires — a direct policy conflict marked as 'no conflicts detected'.", "origin": "primary"}, {"text": "The assessment rates criticality HIGH on workflow-infrastructure grounds, but the ticket's Integration section claims 'downstream consumers read tickets via existing contracts; the refined template is backward-compatible' — the assessment doesn't probe which side of the tension actually holds.", "origin": "primary"}, {"text": "The assessment cites 'downstream consumer touch' as a complexity input but the ticket adds three new event types to research/{topic}/events.log without enumerating who reads events.log or whether existing consumers tolerate new event names.", "origin": "primary"}, {"text": "The assessment rates scope HIGH partly because the ticket enumerates 7 Edges-from-DR-G carryover items, but each carryover is a new behavior — enumeration of additions expands the work surface, not narrows it.", "origin": "primary"}], "dispositions": {"apply": 0, "dismiss": 8, "ask": 0}, "applied_fixes": [], "dismissals": [{"finding_index": 0, "rationale": "Intent is grounded by the ticket's explicit pointer to discovery_source (research/discovery-architectural-posture-rewrite/research.md); the backlog item is not the spec — the spec lives in the source it cites, and research-phase will read it."}, {"finding_index": 1, "rationale": "Hybridization is an explicit user decision per commit 41ff883 'Revert discovery direction from DR-G to DR-1 with 9 carryovers' — a settled choice, not an unresolved tension. Research will treat carryovers as in-scope."}, {"finding_index": 2, "rationale": "Clarify's scope-boundedness rubric assesses problem and behavior bounds (which files, which behaviors in/out), not implementation-level precision — pinning down line counts and exact prose is properly spec-phase work, and the ticket's touch-points list bounds the files and behaviors explicitly."}, {"finding_index": 3, "rationale": "Complexity tier is binary (simple|complex); already at the upper tier. The new bin/ executable reinforces the rating rather than changing it."}, {"finding_index": 4, "rationale": "The MUST-escalation policy applies to skill/prompt prose authoring; ticket-body MUSTs are project-management/spec-tracking language describing what spec.md must contain, not Claude-facing skill prose. The ticket itself enforces the policy on the resulting skill prose via 'New soft gates ship as positive-routing form per CLAUDE.md MUST-escalation policy; no MUST language without effort=high evidence.' Policy bites at spec-authoring time, where compliance is reviewable."}, {"finding_index": 5, "rationale": "Per clarify rubric §5.3, HIGH is the appropriate default for changes to shared skills/workflow infrastructure — backward-compatibility is a risk reducer, not a criticality reducer. The two claims are compatible, not contradictory."}, {"finding_index": 6, "rationale": "Surface-compatibility of new event types is a research-phase question, not a confidence-rating one. Propagating as an Open Question for research: enumerate existing readers of research/{topic}/events.log (events registry, overnight tooling, etc.) and confirm tolerance for new event names."}, {"finding_index": 7, "rationale": "Methodological challenge to the wording, not to the verdict. Scope-boundedness HIGH stands on the explicit per-file touch-points list and the explicit removed-surface line ranges; the enumeration of carryovers is supporting evidence of explicitness, not the load-bearing claim."}], "status": "ok"}
